Civil Rights Movement Launches Travel Warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Benefit of Color People (NAACP) has issued a warning for colored people traveling to Missouri on the basis of the state’s discriminatory principles and racist attacks.
“The NAACP Travel Recommendation for Missouri, effective from August 28, 2017, calls on African American travellers, visitors and residents of Missouri to pay more attention when traveling across the state due to a series of controversial racially motivated incidents currently taking place across the state,” the association said in a statement.
The NAACP said it took this step on the basis of current Missouri laws, which make it harder to defend racist-motivated acts in court, as well as as the actions of law enforcement authorities that disproportionately target minorities.
“Civil rights are being violated.
People are stopped by police just because of their skin color, they are attacked or killed,” said Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP for Missouri.
“We have received the most complaints so far.
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization to the United States.
The incidents the organization cited included racially motivated abuse of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in controversial circumstances earlier this year after he got gasoline on his way across the state and was arrested by police without being charged with committing a crime.
The travel recommendation also highlights a recent statement by the Missouri Supreme Prosecutor’s Office, which states that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped by the police.
“The purpose of the travel recommendation is to alert people and warn their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared – they should carry money with them for a possible deposit or warn their relatives that they are about to travel through the state.”
According to the current figures of the FBI program for reporting hate crimes, there were 100 cases of hateful behavior in Missouri in 2015, making the state 16th among all states.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder to sue a company for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows government officials to detain people on the basis of violations of this law, which, according to the ACLU, aims to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the State Department for foreign countries, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the United States.
