EPA Director Scott Pruitt on Delaying Obama Administration’s Planned Emissions Reduction Directives
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by 15 states, its chief Scott Pruitt withdrew his earlier decision to postpone the implementation of the former Obama administration’s plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes to his plan and responded to the needs of state environmental regulators more quickly than previous governments.
However, he did not mention the legal appeal filed against his previous position at the Federal Court of Appeal.
The deadline was set to October 1, when countries should start implementing the 2015 Regulation on the reduction of ground ozone levels.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interference with local decisions or threatening economic growth.”
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma State Attorney General before President Donald Trump took over as EPA chief, has long served as a reliable opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly shifted or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industry.
The sudden Wednesday turnaround is the biggest legal failure for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, the Federal Court of Appeal in Washington ruled that the EPA executive exceeded its authority in an attempt to delay the inclusion of the Obama administration’s plan that required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released on Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed its version of the ozone standards and reinforced the EPA’s commitment to cooperate with states through comprehensive processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
“During the previous administration, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set up plans,” Pruitt said, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation by means of court litigation and we take compliance with the deadline seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
The EPA statement, however, states that Pruitt may at some point use “the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities” to ensure that regulations “are based on sound policies and the most accessible information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a wider revision of ozone rules.
The White House budget, approved last month, aims to postpone the implementation of 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group did not intend to allow under legal pressure.
“The turn in the EPA’s views – following our court trial – is an important victory for the health and safety of those 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman added.
To New York joined California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground ozone is created when common harmful substances discharged by automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists are grateful for Pruitt’s sudden change.
“It’s worrying how much pressure we need to put on changing the thinking of responsible people and protecting the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biodiversity.
“We must continue to fight the ideological drive of the Trump administration, which seeks to help polluters and special interests.”
