China lacks tourists.
Beijing is losing billions of dollars due to its visa policy.
For decades, China has tried to exercise its influence without the use of force.
It spends $10 billion annually on supporting language schools and building universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry to foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
Beijing is not doing that.
The state media speaks of a plan to make tourism a driving force for economic transformation and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals increased by only 3.8 percent last year, with about 80 percent of tourists coming to China from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is caused, among other things, by the fact that despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, assesses the situation in the world’s most populous country, economics professor at Beijing University Christopher Balding in an article for Bloomberg.
One example of this is China’s visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free visits to China, while citizens of the other countries need to obtain a visa in advance.
Therefore, Chinese officials in the United States have crowds comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
The visa costs $140 but if you don’t want to wait for hours in line, you’ll have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic obstacles.
