How the financial rules of football will affect Neymar's move to Paris
The rules restricting funding for European football clubs will not affect Neymar’s record transfer from Spanish Barcelona to French Paris-Saint-Germain.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by the EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the authority to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The Financial Fair Play Rules (FFP) introduced by UEFA in 2011 stipulate that PSG will have to prove that Neymar’s transfer was not funded without large losses.
Barcelona has paid 222 million euros to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
There are several financial conditions for Neymar's transfer to France.
Given that the PSG team is funded by a wealthy Qatar family that has grown wealthy by selling energy, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already-star football family.
Clubs can spend enormous amounts on purchasing players, but on the other hand they must demonstrate legal sources of income, allowing them to cover the general costs of football-related business activities.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after he became the chair of UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs in the hunt for new reinforcements ended up cheating and risking bankruptcy if the banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, the FFP rules redirected their attention from club debt to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich used with Chelsea in 2003 — to buy a club with potential and spend horrendous amounts on players y to build a global brand — was suddenly not so profitable.
During the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor Aleksander Čeferin is determined to defend the ban on excessive spending.
“The FFP rules are still in place and we are determined to strengthen them in the future,” Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with FFP rules, told Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the amount for Neymar’s redemption in a one-off payment, it may, for accounting purposes, spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be dissolved to €44.4 million annually for five years.
The first wave of the highest FFP sanctions hit PSG in 2014 along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG was fined €60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to €20 million - and ordered to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is looking out for teams that may try to bypass financial regulators by increasing their revenue through companies associated with club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatar company sponsors PSG, once the funding exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the settlement of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it ruled that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
Part of Neymar's income at PSG could, according to some reports, be paid from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
However, PSG and Qatar 2022 officials have denied that Neymat should become the ambassador of the World Cup and that such a manoeuvre would be easily exposed by UEFY officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules.
UEFA did not initiate any investigation into the transfer of Neymar to PSG.
The source wanted to remain anonymous as he was not entitled to comment on the situation with PSG, the Associated Press.
The latest published financial statements show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of €10 million and a turnover of €542.4 million.
The financial statements for the current financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar’s arrival to be a huge opportunity for sponsors, merchandising and the sale of shirts.
The club promises to increase sales by up to 30 percent.
Representatives of the Spanish league, apparently concerned about the departure of one of the biggest stars, sought to ward off Neymar's departure, arguing that PSG would violate the FFP rules.
“This is a clear case of ‘financial doping’ by the club and the state,” La Liga president Javier Teba told the Spanish newspaper AS, referring to the ownership of the club by the Qatar syndicate.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports magnate, shares the same position of La Liga about funding the club.
“It’s the result of a possession that has fundamentally changed the football world over the last 15 years,” Wenger said.
“Once the club’s owner becomes a state, everything is possible.
