NHS to Prescribe Controversial HIV Drug to 10,000 Patients
Patients will get access to ‘transformative’ treatment to prevent HIV from September following a Supreme Court decision to fund the NHS drug.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis pill (PrEP), which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
NSH agreed to fund the trial period after the Court of Appeal endorsed a Supreme Court ruling last year stating that the NHS had the funds to repay PrEP despite statements that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention,” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Additional clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a HIV drug administered before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among the at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
The tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status has not yet been controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also sign up at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will bring taxpayers to £10 million and NHS England has signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after obtaining an international public procurement.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than 30 years of efforts to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of the National Aids Trust, said: “We are witnessing a crucial moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually tested and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to improvements in the quality of many lives.
We welcome this statement with pleasure.”
Ian Green, Chief Executive Officer of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that they are accessible to every patient.
Now we have the test drug PrEP available and we are on the right track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
The following tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it is important that we start testing across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and, together, stop the spread of HIV in society.”
