Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however frightening.
Researchers have now revealed the conclusions of the first finds of an amazing creature the size of a rhinos, whose perfectly preserved remains – which experts have called the “Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs” – were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such an extent that experts were able to determine the red-brown color of its peeled skin and stated that the dinosaur had a “problematic past.”
A paper in the journal Current Biology said it was “the most preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world.”
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. Dinosaurs lived in the Crete period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked researchers, who described him with the words “truly remarkable.”
According to National Geographic, it is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 in the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He stumbled upon something that looked like a foreign object and decided to examine it closer.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1,100 kilograms.
Once the work is completed, the dinosaur is ready to be uncovered.
“It’s enough to shake your eyes a little and you’ll believe it’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown and naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is exhibited.
“It will enter history as one of the most beautiful and most preserved species of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.”
By studying its skin, researchers found that this herbivore — despite being covered with armor and resembling a walking tank — was most likely facing a serious threat from the meat-eating dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a system of masking used by many of today’s animals.
Experts say it allowed him to fuse better with his surroundings and avoid enemies.The system of masking suggests that he was the favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
News of the 110 million-year-old dinosaur family Nodosauridae first appeared in newspapers in May. Currently it is available for inspection at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who spent more than 7,000 hours with his team carefully discovering the fossil.
Thanks to the astonishingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and scratches throughout the body.
They uncovered a method of masking commonly used by today's animals in defense - the top of the animal was darker than its bottom.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the findings of the researchers are surprising, as Borealopelta's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
Thus, it is possible that the dinosaur was such a multitude of predators that evolution has preferred masking over confrontation for survival.
Many of today’s masked animals—e.g. a deer, a zebra, or a ribbon—are much smaller and also more vulnerable to prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to literally fight for their survivors.
“The sale of a giant and heavily armored dinosaur clearly illustrates the dangers that predators posed during the Crete period,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the shells also revealed that the dinosaur’s skin was probably red-brown.
Researchers continue to study the animal and look for further insights about his life, including the preserved content of his stomach, to find out his last meal.
It is believed that the dinosaur after death fell into the river and was taken to the sea, where he sank to the bottom.
The area of Alberta at that time had the same climate as today's Florida, and the rivers and oceans stretched much further into the interior than it is today.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in being completely covered in perfectly preserved peeled skin while being preserved in three dimensions so we can see its original size,” Brown said.
“For these reasons, the animal looks almost the same as it was in Crete.
You don’t have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; you just have to shake your eyes a little and it seems like it’s just asleep.”
During the Crete period, giant teropods, meat-eating dinosaurs, walked through the Earth, moving on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - Tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been the favorite prey of his equally terrifying ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5 meter long monster weighing over 6 tons.
Researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe that the body of Borealopelta was discharged into the sea after being mummified in mud.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, during a drilling in the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, which is also complete from hips to hip.
The animal reached an average length of 5 meters and weighed up to 1300 kg.
From his shoulders emerged two 50 cm thorns.
The researchers believe that this herbivore broke through the territory of today’s Canada until it ended up in the river that flooded it into the sea.
His submarine tomb kept his body in perfect condition.
The fossil remains of this species are preserved to the extent that the armoured plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, “Finding an individual that is so preserved can be compared to winning a lottery.
The longer I look at it, the more shocking it seems to me.
The fossil remains of this species are preserved to the extent that the armoured plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
At his side lies his right front leg with fingers heading upwards.
I can easily count the scales on his feet.”
How did one activist learn the answer to the question: “Who’s the streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her whole body.
The day after she arrived in New York, a fellow from St. Louis sat down on her bed in an Airbnb room and browsed Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across the contribution of a high school student.
“The police just shot an 18-year-old boy whose body still lies on the street,” it read.
She wondered that no one else wrote her this post, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
User @TheePharoah constantly retweeted her posts on the wall.
The St. Louis rapper posted on Twitter his posts about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old boy shot by a white policeman in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown’s body lying out on the street, where no one took him for four hours.
“It’s crazy,” Ferrell thought.
Death was nothing new to her and her family.
She put off the phone to go back to him in the evening as she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the father of the victim and in his hand held a cedar with the inscription “Ferguson police killed my unarmed son!”
She watched live news — one of the policemen stood in front of a group of protesters, holding a clue in his hand, and on his other end a licking dog.
In another video, another police officer, she said, was holding a gun in his hand, targeting the crowd and shouting, “I’ll kill you all... animals.”
“That’s not normal,” said Ferrell.
“This is not the kind of murder we are used to and we can call normal.
I felt the skin all over my body.
“I was angry and I was crying.”
She immediately ordered a flight back and went home the next day.
After landing at 23:00, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided that they would go to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years describes the new documentary “Whose Streets?”, which will be released on August 11.
It’s a story of survival and protests, love and resistance, strength and unbreakability, told from the perspective of people living in a community who come out on the streets and demand answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell established a dialogue with her daughter – dressed in a flower dress and the same flower head – on a topic they had discussed many times before – “the experience with blacks.”
“Do you remember when I taught you how blacks had to fight for what they believed in?” he recalls the interview.
“We’re going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that’s not right.”
“It didn’t seem to me that I’t take her with me,” Ferrell said later.
“Today’s events are the culmination of what happened in the past.
She had to see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but she also needed to know the difference between the different layers of black experience and what we need to do to liberate ourselves.
Despite being able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism on her own, she is in no way different from any other black child-woman.
I feel that if I protected her from this experience, I would only hurt her.”
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop was the South Florissant Road opposite the police station, which became a base for activists waiting for police officer Darren Wilson’s words about his possible involvement in the incident.
Here, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for others.
Together, they prepared food in sacks and helped the Protestants.
A new type of activism slowly began to emerge in Ferrell’s eyes.
“My activism turned upside down after August 9,” Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was the president of the Association of Minority Student Nurses Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural.”
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the later co-director of the document, Sabaah Folayan, during the evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "only document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell asked, “Are you working on a document, or are you trying to find a story that could be used?”
This kind of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to earn on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an interview: “We’ve heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often overlooked and that’s what we wanted to change.”
Folayan has already collaborated with co-director Damon Davis, a respected local artist who deals with prisoners of death.
