A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning’s DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the Fridman Gallery in New York, there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black and brown - hanging from the ceiling on the wires.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from hair and mouth strips sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is titled A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before his departure from the post of President of the United States.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning’s DNA and using 30 portraits to depict what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the subordination of DNA – as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted – and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born as Bradley Edward Manning, has been talking about herself as a woman since her youth. She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of twenty charges, including breaches of six spying laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were detained by the prison staff. Only one lower-quality black-and-white photo leaked to the public, where Manning, apparently concerned, sits on the driver's seat in a platinum-blonde pair she is now associated with.
In 2015 there were still positive reactions to Dewey-Hagborg’s 2012 Stranger Visions project.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects – such as cigarette tickers and chewing gloves – to create an image of possible images of these people.
And it was at that time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They were planning an interview with Chelsea Manning in jail and wanted to add a portrait to the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
Visits or photographs were not allowed, so they turned to Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned mum had been in friendship for two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic titled Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea was pardoned and could attend the show in person.
In fact, a few days after the comic book was released, President Obama requested Manning’s release, a welcome change after several unbearable years spent in a military prison in Kansas.
It’s really interesting that the exhibition takes place at a time when Donald Trump is waging a war with people seeking to disclose government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to incite resentment in areas he should support with his tweets.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the artist’s statement on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her enormous signature (the letter “i” in the last name is streaked by the heart) for the end of “self-dealing fractionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.”
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a stone of the letters C, G, and A recorded with a pencil.
By adding 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist’s sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we are all.
“I hope that people will appreciate that our genome doesn’t matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” Dewey-Hagborg said.
“DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last copy of the exhibition, placed in a separate room, is a single page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging like King Kong from the United States Disciplinary Barracks prison with a megaphone in her hand.
“Once they stop you from speaking, they win,” it says.
“Never be silent.”
“It’s a direct transcription of one of the letters,” said the Philadelphia artist.
“When I think of it, my skin is shaking.”
Manning hasn’t personally visited the exhibition yet—which was predicted in the comic book—but when it happens, she will be welcomed in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genomic imagery, sorted as a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplos groups are recorded with a pencil.
“In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel like a crowd,” Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the shape of Chelsea and liberates her.”
