Startups that will help your company not to become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find a suitable survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees have expressed their mistrust in the entire process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, e-commerce owner of the San Francisco-based hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
He asked for help from the outside.
New HR startups are constantly emerging in the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intention of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, further offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact directors directly.
“There are tools like Strava and Fitbit on the market that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said she has gained greater awareness of what her employees think and feel in three years thanks to Glint.
In addition to quick surveys and team-specific voting, Glint offers a company temperature map and a brief overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as a low-rated manager overview – allowing the user to work on the remedy.
Companies are beginning to realize the need to take care of the workplace culture – in case it becomes another Uber – which is plunging into scandals after a former employee posted a post on his blog describing the company’s environment and harassing employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture research represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let’s Talk Payments website, which looks at technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance sector could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Startup Convercent from Denver, Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before Uber scandals.
Among the 600 customers of Convercent are Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also come under its wings.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “blitz” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If a Director-General is involved in the issue, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
“The public opinion court has authorized regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of ill-treatment of its employees or unethical behavior – and if the regulators do not act – it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycott, employee depletion, or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employee awareness of company policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate leadership.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to search for a telephone number or email to the management of the company, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a deterrent and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday’s chief executive, according to which there was previously no reliable way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses Convercent, it is guaranteed to quickly detect and resolve problems that have never previously reached managers sitting in offices, miles away from actual complaint resolution – such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair treatment.
"It's close to a holistic, overall view of employee experiences," said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday group overseeing risk management.
“At the same time, we protect shareholders from legal disputes by employees.”
Companies stopped taking ethics, values, and employee involvement lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron’s collapse over employee ethics abuse, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “social media came to light” that companies began to realize that in the online world they couldn’t just hide their skeletons in the closet.
“Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which the company pays regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
Convercent raised a total of $10 million from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital in its February campaign and eventually raised $47 million in capital.
Glint earned $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and $60 million over the course of the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing number of surveys clearly confirm that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are not the main advantage.
Employees want to feel that they are received and appreciated and that they dedicate their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“When people are happy in their work, they feel that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of the company,” said Nina McQueen, a vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses Convercent and Glint.
Investors make a profit if a company thrives and companies thrive if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure employee engagement and commitment to the company, it is not surprising that there will be a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to experts on work culture, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company requests feedback from its employees, big changes can occur.
And if the change does not happen quickly – in the worst case at all – it can provoke disappointment and disinterest of employees.
“Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be ready for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, chief consultancy at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies relying too much on the data itself.
“Because once you don’t get things done, employees start asking, ‘Have they heard me at all?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, why should it interest me?”
Madison Reed, which now regularly conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to solve the problem in one day thanks to Glint, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated by the slow decision making and the quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important insight into its employees and hopes to high employment rates in an industry known for frequent dismissals in the long run.
“Unless you strive to create a transparent working environment, employees won’t trust you,” Vitrano added.
“And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company collapses.”
