Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps depicting possessions: “You may think the dispute over land is boring,” Rhodes said, “but I came across one case where two families were dragging over a breeze.
Leave that people!”
Some stories in the book use the castle as a bridge and dive deeper into English history, including The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English uprising of 1381.
