Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle – such as The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by Darrell’s family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about a 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes’ favourite family is the Darrell family: “I was interested in the male generation – men at the time were always indebted and spent money on things they couldn’t afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family have solved this by marrying rich or old ladies—I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to beat their heirs.”
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes seeks further adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stand in the Finnish wilderness, where he was sewing inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was absorbed by nature.
