Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may alleviate symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million U.S. inhabitants and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, however, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that promote intestinal resistance.
Leading the study, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells protect the gut and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that support tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
Once the dishes of the weights tilt to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the scientists found the presence of immune cells supporting the body’s tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan – one of the building blocks of proteins – to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We found a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body’s tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more immune cells they had.”
At the same time, he suggested that if the same proves to be true for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri bacteria and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a type of immune cell supporting body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice bred separately had no cells.
It derived from the fact that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbiome – a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that commonly reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of mice were tested using the DNA sorting method, and the researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
The mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked the intestinal microbiome – they did not develop this type of immune cells – were given L. reuteri bacteria – and they created immune cells.
To understand how the bacterium affects the immune system, the researchers cultivated L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid – without the bacteria – to undeveloped immune cells that were stored in isolation.
The immune cells have developed into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the fluid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-octic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us hold L. reuteri bacteria in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been detected in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Everyone of us should probably strive for the development of these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the cell population.
