A British inventor uses a microchip in his hand to unlock a car and a house.
The British inventor became the first person in the country to have a microchip right in the body. by just shaking his hand he can unlock the door from home and office and even start a car.
Thirty-three-year-old Steven Northam implanted a tiny chip between his thumb and his index and is now offering the same service through his BioTeq company to companies and individuals who want to make their lives easier with technology.
The procedure of implantation and treatment is supervised by Dr. Geoff Watson, anesthesiologist at the Royal Hampshire County Hospital in Winchester.
The technology works on the same principle as microchips implanted to dogs and cats, and the entire procedure takes 30 seconds.
Northam also offers a service for replacing microchip-compatible door and car locks.The price of one lock is £300.
