White House recovery cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House’s decision to fly a navy helicopter to South Lawn on the occasion of the U.S. manufacturing industry celebration last month came at $24,000, according to Navy records released by the weekly TIME.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the culmination of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials visited a product show from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire car, and a fork-shaped lifting wheel from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the helicopter to be present less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an “extraordinary” event, records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) — the unit responsible for managing the helicopter — said.
“I wanted to make sure you are aware of such a significant event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy’s Deputy Air Force Commander, the day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 about 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to start at 15:00 and will remain on site until the entire site was completely cleared, which was scheduled between 18:00 and 21:00.
The e-mail also stated that if there was a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for a return flight due to working hours regulations.
The original crew remained on the spot that evening along with the helicopter and with them also a unit of security personnel.
From the records – obtained by the weekly TIME – it was not clear whether the second crew was eventually sent as well.
The Hatch Act prohibits government officials from using government assets for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
“We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was okay,” the commander wrote.
“It sounds like you’re blocked,” the deputy commander wrote.
This “Made in America” show was designated by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But even the official events have political subtext.
During his participation in the events, the president promoted the health care reform that was going through the Senate and spoke of an effort to keep the government’s regulations on track.
The use of aircraft such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
They use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane flew in the background at his first first meeting as part of the campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is pleased with the ‘Made in America’ show, which showcased products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, the deputy press secretary.
The crew of the HMX-1 helicopters often train landings in the area of Washington and South Lawn and train possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with the utmost accuracy.
While Trump attended the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 exercise landings near the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the current training of the crew, a state official said.
The helicopter unit flew on the same day for another eleven hours as part of “non-presidential support missions”.
The White House said no additional receipts had been paid from taxpayers’ money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not in any way interested in negotiations on the exposure of the helicopter at South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the show is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Ministry of Defense, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017 is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records show the time 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are much below that amount.
“It is very misleading to state taxpayers’ costs on the basis of estimates for reimbursement,” Walters said.
“These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in annual costs.”
According to the 2015 RAND study, reimbursements for DoD expenses do not include staff costs, but include fuel price, maintenance and contract costs.
White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated the use of a helicopter for the show.
“The idea of the show that takes place this week is to introduce products made in the US,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to contribute to the defense of our state and to provide jobs for hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact should be remembered.”
It is unclear whether Trump was also looking at the helicopter during his flight to South Lawn. It can only be said with certainty that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire cars.
Back in the White House, Trump addressed a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” said the president, “I own three.”
