UN says Afghan democracy relies on women in politics
The elections can only be credible if all members of society, including women, participate, a UN representative in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, a senior UN Relief Mission official, said hundreds of women participated in local parliamentary elections, three women are running for vice president and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
“The role of women cannot be overlooked,” he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be fully representative and credible if women participate in them, as well as in all related processes related to the elections.
Presidential and local elections will be held in Afghanistan on April 5.
The Taliban has issued a number of threats against the electoral process, which is shifting international fighting to the other corner.
This year, for the first time ever, a democratically elected government has handed over its power to a peacefully succeeding government.
Haysom said that a strong role of women will strengthen Afghanistan’s democracy.
The Afghan Independent Electoral Commission said that of the total 3.6 million registered voters, 1.2 million are women.
