Discover the plant with one click.
Students with the creation of herbaries and ordinary lovers of plants will be helped by the new free application Pl@ntNet.
When they are wondering what kind of plant they’ve just stumbled upon on a walk, this app will help them.
All they have to do is photograph the plant and the app will recognize what species it is.
The new app, which is available for iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the Centre for Ethical and Environmental Education CEEV in Bratislava Horský Park in the framework of the Secret Life of the City project.
Students from 50 Czech and Slovak schools were also involved in the project, who together with teachers photographed and added plants from their surroundings to the application’s database.
The newly created French app is free to download from the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French programmers was to get as many people as possible to contribute to the app with their images, thus increasing the number of plants that the app can recognize.
“Already children who hold a tablet or a mobile phone in their hands can go to the forest,” said Ivana Poláčková, coordinator of the project.
Based on a sufficiently high-quality photo of a flower, leaf or fruit of a plant, the application can recognize its name within a few seconds, which then in Czech and Slovak will be assigned under the photo.
The French allowed us to translate the app into Slovak and Czech for the Secret Life of the City project.
It is therefore welcome for users to contribute with an image of a plant that is not yet found in the database after creating an account in the application.
“The French will assess whether it is beneficial, and then add it to the database,” Poláčková said.
GMB worries about investment in McVitie's Glasgow factory
The trade unions are demanding assurances from the managers of McVitie’s cookie manufacturer about the long-term commitment of the production at the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish trade union GMB said the company has been silent about a possible investment in the Tollcross plant.
The factory employs more than 500 employees who produce, among other products, Hobnob and Rich Tea cookies.
McVitie’s owner, Pladis, said it has invested more than £5 million in the entire area over the past few years.
She added that employees and trade union representatives will be “among the first to be informed” in the event of changes in the operation of the factory.
In a letter to the company’s construction manager, GMB’s Scottish unions expressed concerns that McVitie’s “will not meet its promises of financing and upgrading its production lines.”
GMB Chief Organizer Drew Duffy added: “The fact that we have not received a clear answer from the construction manager regarding the needs of the company and the future investment plan in Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families have worked here, and the employees are mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where work at the factory represents a critical pillar of decent employment in areas from high unemployment and social exclusion.
From the point of view of labor, wages and profitability — and despite the outlook for Brexit, rising cost of living and falling slow production — the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately thriving producer like McVitie’s.”
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: “Tollcross received a letter from GMB yesterday and the company will make a statement as soon as possible as we value the continued commitment to employees and trade union representatives.
A regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tollcross took place two months ago and many issues were openly discussed at this meeting.
We talked to our employees that as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we evaluate our operations on a regular basis, which applies to all our operations, so that we can continue to successfully compete with others.
She added: “Over the past few years, we have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area, in production lines and operational efficiency.
We highly value the heritage of Tollcross and the site, and in case of any changes in the operation of the factory, employees and trade union representatives will be informed immediately.”
